<br />
Also 1 year is a lot different then 40 years.  Doing the same thing every year for 40 years is different then doing it for one year.  This was my point.  <br />
<br />
The way the US tax system works, what your tax is for year X is the amount they require you to pay in for year X + 1, through estimates and/or with holdings, unless you are very very certain you will have a dramatic change in income that will decrease your tax burden.  As a result, this is not something you can do every year, it is something you can do for maybe one year. <br><BR><font size=1>21:11 02-20-2011</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Serpent </B></font><br><font class="afont"> <A HREF='/vs/resources/buzz.php?ignorename=Serpent '>Ignore</A></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">Getting 1% extra throughout the year by paying on April 15th, and then doing that for 40 years, is different than a 40 year time horizon?<br />
